n" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">Metropolitan Desk Correction </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Metropolitan Desk; SECTA</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Here to Help; Answering Your Burning Questions on Climate Change</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Q: WHY AREN'T THERE CLIMATE DAMAGE LAWSUITS LIKE THE TOBACCO LITIGATION?</Para><Para>Brigid Shea, Austin, Tex.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>A: A NUMBER OF CLIMATE LAWSUITS AND INVESTIGATIONS ARE GOING ON, BOTH IN THE UNITED STATES AND AROUND THE WORLD.</Para><Para>Some have parallels to the tobacco litigation of the 1990s that led to a multibillion-dollar settlement with states. The state suits claimed that the tobacco industry lied about the dangers of smoking and was responsible for billions of dollars in increased Medicaid costs. Cities and counties have now filed lawsuits against fossil fuel companies arguing along similar lines that the industry is contributing to the effects of climate change and that government entities are having to pay the costs -- including those of dealing with sea level rise, drought and other weather extremes.</Para><Para>Most of the lawsuits originate in blue states along the coasts. The first were filed by Marin and San Mateo Counties and the City of Imperial Beach, all in California. Others have followed, including suits from San Francisco and Oakland and one filed in January by New York City. Former Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger of California says he will get into the act, as well, announcing this week that he is planning a suit against oil companies for ''first-degree murder.'' He was vague on the details of such a suit or when he might file it, however.</Para><Para>And a group of young plaintiffs is suing the United States government, demanding that it do more to fight climate change. The suit, first filed during the Obama administration, has gained even more importance for activists during the Trump administration. This administration filed an unusual request with the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit asking the court to stop the case. The three-judge panel refused, and the case could begin in Eugene, Ore., before the end of the year. JOHN SCHWARTZ</Para><Para>Do you have questions about climate change? We answer them in the Climate Fwd: newsletter. Sign up at nytimes.com/newsletters.</Para><Para>This is a more complete version of the story than the one that appeared in print.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">DRAWING </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

